Where are we?

In this video we continue our discussion of regression methods. In the last video and in class this week, you were introduced to non-parametric algorithms, specifically K-nearest neighbors. Today we will learn another non-parametric algorithm called Multivariate Adaptive Regression Splines, or MARS for short.

MARS: Main idea

The goal of MARS is to create a piecewise linear model so that the relationship between a predictor and the response can be different for different ranges of the predictor variable. This method can also be extended to multiple predictor variables.

The black line in this graph is the MARS model with 4 cut points. Between the cut-points a different ordinary least squares line is fit in such a way that there is one continuous function. So, we see this model allows a positive relationship between x and y when x is between 0 and just greater than one and a negative relationship when x is between 2 and 4.

Hinge functions

For a cut-point \(a\), define a pair of hinge functions, \(h(x-a)\) and \(h(a-x)\) as:

\[ h(x-a) = \begin{cases} x-a,& x\gt a\\ 0, & x \le a \end{cases} = (x-a) * I(x>a) \\ h(a-x) = \begin{cases} a-x,& x\lt a\\ 0, & x \ge a \end{cases} = (a-x) * I(x<a) \]

Estimate a coefficients using ordinary least squares

\[ \begin{align} \hat{y} &= \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 \Big[(x - a) * I(x>a)\Big] + \hat{\beta}_2 \Big[(a-x) I(x < a)\Big] \\ &= \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 h(x-a) + \hat{\beta}_2 h(a-x) \end{align} \]

Hinge functions are a key part of MARS models. For a cut-point \(a\) define a pair of hinge functions, \(h(x-a)\) and \(h(a-x)\) as follows: \(h(x-a) = x-a\) when \(x\) is greater than \(a\), otherwise it is zero; and \(h(a-x) = a-x\) when \(x\) is less than \(a\), otherwise it is zero. This pair of hinge functions create two new variables which can be used in a linear model and will create a piecewise linear function. Lets look at an example with the sample data.

Hinge example

We want to estimate:

\[ \tiny \begin{align} y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{\Big[(2-x) I(x < 2)\Big]}_{x_1} + \beta_2 \underbrace{\Big[(x - 2) * I(x>2)\Big]}_{x_2} \end{align} \]

Create the new variables

df2 <- df %>% 
  mutate(x1 = (2 - x) * as.numeric(x<2),
         x2 = (x - 2) * as.numeric(x>2))
x y x1 x2

2.33 0.67 0.00 0.33
1.75 0.55 0.25 0.00
0.44 0.63 1.56 0.00




Fit the model

MARS term estimate
(Intercept) (Intercept) 0.74
h(2-x) x1 -0.14
h(x-2) x2 -0.51

In this example, we create a hinge function at \(x=2\). First, we create the two new variables, \(x_1\) and \(x_2\). Notice in the sample of data shown in the table that observations where \(x > 2\) have \(x_1\) values of 0 and observations where \(x < 2\) have \(x_2\) values of 0.

Then we fit the ordinary least squares regression model with the new variables, \(x_1\) and \(x_2\). The model results are shown in the table and the graph. We can clearly see that the line is piecewise linear and that the hinge occurs at 2. The coefficients can be difficult to interpret directly, but the graph gives a good visual of the fit.

Choosing the cut points

Here we show the the models for various cut points. Are any of these the best cut point? How is the initial cut-point determined? Each data point for each possible predictor is evaluated as a candidate cut-point. So, in this example, we only have one possible predictor but over 400 candidate cut-points.

The hinge functions are created for each candidate cut-point and the regression model is fit. Then, the predictor and cut-point with the smallest sum of squared residuals is chosen as the best model.

After that cut-point is decided, then the rest of the data points for the predictor that was used initially and all other predictors are once again considered as the second cut-point. Once again, the model with the smallest sum of squared residuals, which will have two cut-points, is chosen as the best model.

The process continues until some user-defined stopping point is reached. The default is that \(R^2\) is increased by less than .001.

It turns out that neither \(x = 2\) nor \(x = 3\) is the best cut-point for these data. Youll also be happy to learn that we dont have to do this process by hand. We can use functions from the caret package to help us find out what the best cut-point is.

Finding the first and second cut-points

The table in the top left shows the MARS model for just one cut-point, at \(x = 1.17\). This cut-point produces the model with the smallest sum of squared residuals. This is shown in orange in the graph on the right.

The table in the bottom left shows the MARS model for two cut points, \(x = 1.17\), which was the best initial cut-point, and \(x = 4.89\). This is shown in purple in the graph on the right.

Tuning the model

term estimate
(Intercept) 0.96
h(1.17101-x) -0.75
h(x-4.88552) 1.07

h(x-4.19299) 0.54

nprune RMSE
2 0.456
3 0.350
4 0.300
5 0.298
6 0.299

In the MARS algorithm, cut-points and hinge-functions are sequentially added to the model until the \(R^2\) increases by less than .001, which means that additional cut-point is barely increasing the amount of variation in the response explained by the model.

At that point, the algorithm goes back to evaluate each of the hinge functions and sequentially removes any that are not contributing. Often it will remove one of the hinge function pairs. That happened with this model as the \(h(x-1.17101)\) function was removed.

Example: King County Housing

nprune RMSE

Here, we fit a MARS model to the King County house price data. To keep it simple, we only allowed it to use the variables bedrooms, sqft_living, sqft_lot, and yr_built.

We can see both in the table and the graph of cross-validated RMSE, the best model using cross-validation used 4 terms. Here, terms includes the intercept. So, there are 3 coefficients for hinge functions plus the intercept.

The table at the top shows the resulting MARS model that was described previously.

We can use partial dependence plots to visualize the modeled relationship between each of the predictor variables and the response, holding all other variables at their mean value.

So, the plot on the left shows the modeled relationship between sqft_living and price, holding yr_built at the average year built for all observations. We can clearly see where the cut-points occur in the plots.

Summary

  • MARS models fit piecewise linear models.

  • The resulting model can often still be interpreted nicely.

  • More complex MARS models can be fit that include categorical variables and interaction terms.

MARS models fit piecewise linear models. These offer a nice balance between ordinary least squares regression and more complex non-parametric methods. The resulting model can often still be interpreted nicely, but we have more flexibility than with ordinary least squares. We can also fit more complex MARS models that include categorical variables and interaction terms.
